es for understanding a changing global system as the US, the chief advocate of nonproliferation and a central node in the diplomatic networks around it, declines in material power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 0aNuclear nonproliferationxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNuclear nonproliferationxInternational cooperationxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Arms Control.2bisacsh  aEgypt.  aEurope.  aSouth Africa.  aTreaty on Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons.  aUnited States.  adiplomacy.  aextension.  anetwork theory.  anonproliferation.  anuclear weapons.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362964640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503629646423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503629646/original  a978-3-11-073914-5  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles